<DocPageMeta Title="The mapping abstraction"
             Section="Concepts"
             Order="40"
             Status="DocPageStatus.Draft"
             Description="How the repository translates between entities and DTOs, what IShiftEntityMapper is, and how to choose between AutoMapper, Manual, Mapperly, and Mapster mapping strategies."
             Keywords="mapping,mapper,ishiftentitymapper,automapper,manual,mapperly,mapster,strategy,dto,entity" />

<DocSection Title="Why a mapping abstraction">
    <p>
        Repositories spend most of their time translating between two shapes:
        the <b>entity</b> (what the database stores) and the <b>DTO</b> (what
        crosses the wire). For a long time, Shift Framework hard-coded
        AutoMapper as the way to do that translation. That created two problems:
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li>
            <b>Implicit flattening risk.</b> AutoMapper silently maps
            <code>Vehicle.VIN</code> into <code>VehicleVIN</code> via naming
            convention, which can leak data unintentionally. There's no compile-time
            check that the mapping you got is the mapping you wanted.
        </li>
        <li>
            <b>Runtime errors.</b> Mapping bugs surface at runtime when the
            mapper actually runs, not at build time when you'd prefer to catch them.
            Forgetting to register a profile typically blows up on the first request
            against the affected endpoint.
        </li>
    </ul>

    <p>
        The solution: introduce <code>IShiftEntityMapper</code> as the single
        mapping abstraction that the repository talks to. AutoMapper becomes
        one possible implementation rather than the only one. Consumers can
        choose between AutoMapper, hand-written manual mappers, source-generated
        Mapperly mappers, or Mapster — picking whatever trade-off fits the
        project — and the repository code stays identical.
    </p>
</DocSection>

<DocSection Title="The interface">
    <p>The contract is four methods:</p>

    <DocCodeBlock Code="@(@"public interface IShiftEntityMapper<TEntity, TListDTO, TViewDTO>
{
    TViewDTO MapToView(TEntity entity);
    TEntity MapToEntity(TViewDTO dto, TEntity existing);
    IQueryable<TListDTO> MapToList(IQueryable<TEntity> query);
    void CopyEntity(TEntity source, TEntity target);
}")" />

    <ul>
        <li><code>MapToView</code> — translate a single entity into its View+Upsert DTO. Used after a save and on get-by-id endpoints.</li>
        <li><code>MapToEntity</code> — merge an incoming DTO into an existing tracked entity. The repository hands you the entity (empty for inserts, loaded for updates) and you populate its fields from the DTO.</li>
        <li><code>MapToList</code> — project an <code>IQueryable&lt;TEntity&gt;</code> into an <code>IQueryable&lt;TListDTO&gt;</code>. <b>Crucially still an IQueryable</b>, so EF Core can translate the projection into a SELECT clause and pull only the columns the list DTO needs.</li>
        <li><code>CopyEntity</code> — entity-to-entity field copy, used by <code>ReloadAfterSave</code> to merge a freshly-loaded entity with navigation properties back onto the tracked instance.</li>
    </ul>

    <DocCallout Type="DocCalloutType.Note">
        <code>MapToList</code> is the only method that has to operate on
        <code>IQueryable</code> rather than concrete instances. This is what
        keeps list endpoints efficient — without it, the framework would have
        to load entire entities into memory and project in C#, defeating
        the OData query pipeline.
    </DocCallout>
</DocSection>

<DocSection Title="The four supported strategies">
    <p>
        Shift Framework's <code>StockPlusPlus</code> sample ships working
        mappers for all four strategies, and you can switch between them at
        runtime via <code>appsettings.json</code>. Each one is a different
        trade-off between how much boilerplate you write, what gets caught at
        compile time versus runtime, and how much hidden behavior the framework
        applies on your behalf.
    </p>

    <h3>1. AutoMapper (the historical default)</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><b>Pros:</b> Convention-based mapping. Zero per-field code for entities whose DTOs match by name. Familiar to most .NET developers.</li>
        <li><b>Cons:</b> The conventions are exactly the problem — silent flattening, runtime-only errors, no compile-time guarantee that a property is mapped. Adds runtime reflection overhead.</li>
        <li><b>When to pick it:</b> Greenfield projects that can lean fully into the conventions, or existing projects already invested in AutoMapper profiles.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>2. Manual</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><b>Pros:</b> Full explicit control. No magic. The mapping is just C# code you can step through with a debugger. Completely compile-time safe.</li>
        <li><b>Cons:</b> Verbose. Every field is typed twice (once on the DTO, once in the mapper). Refactoring an entity means manually updating every mapping site.</li>
        <li><b>When to pick it:</b> Projects with complex mappings that don't fit conventions (e.g. heavy use of <code>ShiftEntitySelectDTO</code>, <code>ShiftFileDTO</code>, JSON columns, computed values), or teams that strongly prefer "no magic."</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>3. Mapperly (source-generated)</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><b>Pros:</b> A Roslyn source generator emits the mapper at compile time. Zero runtime reflection. Compile-time errors when source and target don't line up. Fast.</li>
        <li><b>Cons:</b> Adds a source-generator dependency. Some framework-specific patterns (FK conversions, file DTOs, navigation property projections) still need to be hand-written wrappers around the generated scalar mapping. The generated code is bound to the exact field names — renames need a recompile.</li>
        <li><b>When to pick it:</b> Performance-sensitive projects, or teams that want compile-time mapping safety without writing every field by hand.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>4. Mapster</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><b>Pros:</b> Fluent <code>TypeAdapterConfig</code> API. Much more concise than Mapperly's per-field attribute style. Easy migration from AutoMapper because the mental model is similar (convention-based with explicit overrides).</li>
        <li><b>Cons:</b> Same convention-based flattening risk as AutoMapper, just with a different API. Still requires explicit ignore lists for base class properties and circular navigation references.</li>
        <li><b>When to pick it:</b> Migrating from AutoMapper but wanting better runtime performance and a more controllable surface.</li>
    </ul>
</DocSection>

<DocSection Title="Switching strategies via appsettings">
    <p>
        The default <code>shift</code> template registers all four mapping
        strategies in DI but only activates one of them based on a config
        setting. To switch, edit
        <code>YourApp.API/appsettings.json</code>:
    </p>

    <DocCodeBlock Language="json" Code="@(@"{
    ""MappingStrategy"": ""Manual""
}")" />

    <p>
        Valid values are <code>AutoMapper</code> (default), <code>Manual</code>,
        <code>Mapperly</code>, and <code>Mapster</code>. The
        <code>Program.cs</code> composition root reads this setting and
        registers the matching mapper implementation as
        <code>IShiftEntityMapper&lt;TEntity, TListDTO, TViewDTO&gt;</code> for
        each entity. The repository's two-constructor pattern (one accepting
        <code>IShiftEntityMapper</code>, one falling back to AutoMapper) does
        the rest — DI picks the explicit mapper when it's registered.
    </p>

    <DocCallout Type="DocCalloutType.Tip">
        Switching strategies is a runtime decision per project, not a
        framework-wide one. Two projects in the same organization can use
        different strategies based on their needs. The framework's
        <code>ShiftRepository</code> code is identical regardless.
    </DocCallout>
</DocSection>

<DocSection Title="Mapping helpers (for manual and Mapperly)">
    <p>
        Hand-writing mappers gets tedious fast for entities with audit fields,
        foreign keys, and file references — these patterns repeat for every
        mapper you write. <code>ShiftEntity.Core</code> ships a small set of
        extension method helpers that take the boilerplate away while keeping
        the mapping itself explicit:
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li><code>dto.MapBaseFields(entity)</code> — copies <code>ID</code>, <code>IsDeleted</code>, and the four audit fields from entity to view DTO. Returns the DTO for fluent chaining.</li>
        <li><code>id.ToSelectDTO(text)</code> — converts a foreign key (<code>long</code> or <code>long?</code>) into a <code>ShiftEntitySelectDTO</code> with both the ID and the navigation property's display label.</li>
        <li><code>selectDTO.ToForeignKey()</code> / <code>.ToNullableForeignKey()</code> — the reverse: pull the underlying <code>long</code>/<code>long?</code> back out of a SelectDTO.</li>
        <li><code>json.ToShiftFiles()</code> / <code>files.ToJsonString()</code> — convert between a JSON column and a <code>List&lt;ShiftFileDTO&gt;</code> for entities that store file metadata in a JSON blob.</li>
        <li><code>source.ShallowCopyTo(target)</code> — reflection-based shallow copy of all settable properties; used by manual implementations of <code>CopyEntity</code> for the <code>ReloadAfterSave</code> path.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
        With these helpers, a typical manual mapper for a Product entity looks
        roughly like:
    </p>

    <DocCodeBlock Code="@(@"public ProductDTO MapToView(Product entity)
{
    return new ProductDTO
    {
        Name = entity.Name,
        Price = entity.Price,

        // Foreign key + display label in one call
        ProductCategory = entity.ProductCategoryID
            .ToSelectDTO(entity.ProductCategory?.Name),

        ProductBrand = entity.ProductBrandID
            .ToSelectDTO(entity.ProductBrand?.Name),
    }
    .MapBaseFields(entity);   // ID + audit fields, fluent
}")" />

    <p>
        The result is mapping code that's still explicit (every field is
        visible) but doesn't drown in <code>CreateDate = entity.CreateDate</code>
        repetitions.
    </p>
</DocSection>

<DocSection Title="A practical recommendation">
    <p>
        If you're starting a new project today, the honest recommendation is:
    </p>
    <ul>
        <li>
            <b>Start with AutoMapper</b> if you're learning the framework and
            want the lowest friction. The default template registers it; you
            don't have to think about it.
        </li>
        <li>
            <b>Switch to Manual</b> the moment you hit a mapping bug that
            should have been a compile error, or the moment you find yourself
            hand-coding around a flattening rule. Manual is the most boring,
            most predictable choice — and "boring and predictable" is what you
            want from a mapping layer.
        </li>
        <li>
            <b>Use Mapperly</b> if you have measured a real bottleneck in
            mapping performance and need to eliminate runtime reflection. Don't
            reach for it speculatively.
        </li>
        <li>
            <b>Use Mapster</b> if you're migrating an existing AutoMapper
            project and want a similar API with better runtime characteristics.
        </li>
    </ul>
</DocSection>

